Objective: is to build a neural network-based classifier to determine whether the customer will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Context: Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

Install shap, tensorflow, keras, hipplot and other necessary package

Adding layers [layers and activations]

Keras layers can be added to the model

Adding layers are like stacking lego blocks one by one

It should be noted that as this is a classification problem, sigmoid layer (softmax for multi-class problems) should be added

RandomUniform initializer is used as kernel initializer and bias initializer as zeros Input layer with 10 neuron for 10 attributes and two hiiden llayer with 100 and 50 neurons respectively and one neuron in the output layer as it has to predict 1 or o only

Tried activation function with Adam and adagrad as well Learning rate with .01 and .001 as well

model.add(Dense(50, activation = 'tanh'))

def build_model(hp):
    initializer = tf.keras.initializers.RandomUniform(minval=0., maxval=1.)
    model_1 = tf.keras.Sequential() #Start model
    model_1.add(Dense(units=hp.Int('units_in',min_value=16,max_value=256,step=32),  
                    input_shape = (10,), 
                    activation = hp.Choice('act_in', ['relu', 'tanh']), kernel_initializer = initializer, bias_initializer= 'zeros')) # Hidden Layer connected to Input Layer
    for i in range(hp.Int('num_layers', 0, 2)):
      model_1.add(Dense(units=hp.Int('units_' + str(i),
                                            min_value=32,
                                            max_value=512,
                                            step=32),
                               activation=hp.Choice('act_' + str(i), ['relu', 'tanh'])))  # Hidden Layer
      model_1.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout', 0, 0.5, step=0.1, default=0.3))) # Drop out layer for regularization

    model_1.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')) # Output layer
      
    model_1.compile(
         optimizer=optimizers.Adam(
             hp.Choice('learning_rate', [1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])),
             loss='binary_crossentropy',
             metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model_1

Conclusion: Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem i.e. Obective is to predict the customers one who may leave the bank based on the available dataset and provide proactive counselling and improve the bank services to retain them.

It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc.

In which Row number and CustomerId are the Unique identification key for different customers and which is not contributing to predict the target variable so these columns are dropped.

Insight from the Bivariate Analysis:

The target variable Exited is highly influenced by age, balance and to some extent by an estimated salary as well. negatively correlated with the credit score, tenure and gender too. Geography and balance is having minimal multicolinearity but as such amongst the attributes there is no much correlation. Each independant attributes is impotant to predict the target attribute. From the feature importance perspective Age, Balance and Estimated salary are the three important attributes to predict the target variable "Exited"

With respect to data distribution is concerened data is distributed with 80:20 ratio for the Not Exited and Exited

Model Building

Adding layers are like stacking lego blocks one by one

It should be noted that as this is a classification problem, sigmoid layer (softmax for multi-class problems) should be added

RandomUniform initializer is used as kernel initializer and bias initializer as zeros.

Input layer with 10 neuron for 10 attributes and two hidden layer with 100 and 50 neurons respectively and one neuron in the output layer as it has to predict 1 or o only

Tried activation function with Adam and Adagrad as well Learning rate with .01 and .001 as well where with Adam optimizer given good accuracy and recall and precision values.

Normalisation and preprocessing: is been done. Applied standard scaler and min_max scaler both produced alomst the same result so considered standard scaler for normalisation in order to bring all the attributes to a uniform scaling and to produce better results.

Deep Neural networks with Sequential model is been used and tried with different activation function like relu and tanh with different learning rates .01 and .001 and tried with different batch sizes with different epochs which includes and FP and BP. For the training data set it produces 85% accuracy where in validation data set 79% accuracy. Sequential model with Adams optimizer with all the above performance tuning is able to achieve Accuracy Model1 (Dropout): 0.828 or 82.8% for the test data Recall_score: 0.3132530120481928 Precision_score: 0.6878306878306878 F-score: 0.43046357615894043
